Charge difference densities (CDD) and charge transfer lengths (
Δ R
) of pristine GQD and pyridinic, pyrrolic, and graphitic NGQDs. Blue and red colors represent the positive holes and negative electrons, respectively.

ce:section.ce:para:
X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) studies have revealed that the NGQDs consist mainly of graphitic N, pyridinic N, and pyrrolic N [31,33,35]. Therefore, computational models of three different C–N configurations in NGQDs are considered, as shown in Fig. 1
                         (a)–(d). In all three C–N configurations, the nitrogen atoms are bonded with carbon neighbors via sp [2] hybridizations. In particular, the graphitic N forms three σ bonds with neighboring carbon atoms neighbors [31]; the pyridinic N forms one σ bond and one π bond with neighboring carbon atoms and thus contributes one p electron to the π system of the GQD [61]; the pyrrolic N forms σ bonds with neighboring carbon atoms, where the lone pair p-electrons of N are delocalized over the pyrrole ring and contribute to the π system of the GQD [61]. The average C–C bond lengths (∼1.42 Å) in three NGQDs are almost the same as in pristine GQDs, consistent with previous studies [39,62]. However, a significant structural deformation is observed in pyrrolic NGQD, which is not flat planar compared to the other NGQDs. Such deformation breaks the lattice symmetry, leading to a more localized distribution of electron densities in frontier orbitals of pyrrolic NGQD (Fig. 2
                        ). Such geometrical characteristic of pyrrolic NGQD is consistent with the previous theoretical predictions [63,64].
